 Description

This workflow will backup an existing database to a local or network share file.  The default deployment will only show required parameters.

 Required Inputs

    Server Target - The desired target to run this flow against.
    Server Target Username - The user to login to the Server Target as.
    Server Target Password - The password to login as the Server Target Username.
    Download Source Host - The target host where the files needed for this flow can be downloaded from.
    Download Source Path - The path to where the files can be found on the Download Source Host.
    Database.Name - No description
    Instance.Name - No description
    Target Backup Path - *Required. The full path to a database backup file on a shared Windows network drive.

 Optional Inputs

    Clean Code Base - Remove code base from target after execution (True || False).
    Clean JRE - Remove JRE from target after execution (True || False).
    Debug Level - Set level of output [(least) 1-5 (most)]
    Backup Description - No description
    Windows Share User - No description
    Retention Days - No description
    Perform Integrity Check - Optional. If set to "YES", workflow will only run Pre-Restore Validation.  Use this mode to discover the original data and log files used for the database backup.  Acceptable values\: Yes, No
    Windows Share Password - No description
    Expiration Date - No description
    Compress Backup File - Optional. If set to "YES", workflow will reindex the database after Restore is successfully completed. Acceptable values\: Yes, No
    Backup Encryption Password - Optional.  If the backup file is encrypted with a password, provide password.  To prevent the password from showing in the Deployment screen, use a password-based Policy.
    Instance Password - Optional - The password of the Windows account that will be performing the patch operation.
    Backup Name - No description

 Dependencies

A SQL Server 2008/2008 R2/2012/2014 instance should already be provisioned.
Database backup path should be accessible locally, or on Windows network share.
   If the workflow fails to backup to the path, then the SQL Service is running as an account that cannot access the path (like LocalSystem).  Change the running service to an admin-level account, and try again.  The Provisioning workflows have an advanced parameter called SQL Service Account/Password that the user can set to a user with admin rights.

 Results Verification

- In the last step, the workflow verifies that the backup file exists and is accessible.
- Connect to the target instance via a command-line tool (like sqlcmd) or GUI-based program (like SQL Server Management Studio).  Run "RESTORE VERIFYONLY FROM DISK\='' " to verify that the backup file exists and is accessible.



 Additional Documentation

Additional information, including the _HP Database and Middleware Automation Support Matrix_ and solution pack user guides, are available via HP Live Network\:

"http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation"\:http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation

To access the documentation, click the RESOURCES link and enter your HP Passport credentials.
